I&#39;ve ran into an optimistic locking failure with a Hibernate-managed entity in a Spring web application. At some point, there was a change to that entity which resulted in an increment of its version number. In the debugger of the IDE I recognized that the incremented version was properly available in the underlying repo, but not in the instance itself. Additionally, when querying the repo during debugging, the returned entity was a different one compared to that in the currently executed codepath. That concrete instance was additionally used by callers to be updated again, but as it contained an older version number, the optimistic locking exception was thrown.

Though, that didn&#39;t happen always, in slightly different code paths things worked as expected: The entity was forwarded to the first update and its version number was properly incremented not only in the repo, but that of the instance as well. So callers could easily update the same entity instance over and over again without any problems. Additionally, during debugging and querying the repo at the same place again, really the same entity instance was returned, containing the updated version number. In the first example and code path above a different instance was returned instead and only that new instance had the correct version number.

The following is a snippet of the first change increasing the version number. Depending on the tested scenario, after `updateChanged` the available person instance either contained the updated version number or not.

```java
public void delete(final Address address) {
	ObjectUtils.ifNotNull(address.getPerson(), person -&gt; {
		personService.updateChanged(person);   &lt;- increases version number
		person.getAddresses().remove(address); &lt;- debugging
	});
```

Debugging was done in IntelliJ, which provides an evaluation dialog to additionally query things and I used that to check the repo for the concrete person instance using the following code. Depending on the tested scenario, this either returned a different person instance from the one in the code path and with an updated version number or the same person instance with the same updated version number.

```java
personRepository.findById(UUID.fromString(&quot;[...]&quot;)).get();
```

What other callers did additioonally change in the person instance is not of too much interest, but the transaction handling between the two code paths instead most likely. Scenario one triggering the optimistic locking exception did the following:

```java
