You need to tell the JSON library you are using with Spring how to parse the `createdAt` field.

If you are using Jackson then the `JsonFormat` annotation would do the trick if you really want `LocalDateTime` but as the first comment suggested there are better alternatives like `Instant` or `ZonedDateTime` which will also work with the following:

```java
...

@JsonFormat(pattern = &quot;yyyy-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;)
private LocalDateTime createdAt;

...

```

if you are using GSON you need to write a deserializer like:

```java

class MyDateDeserializer implements JsonDeserializer&lt;LocalDateTime&gt; {

    @Override
    public LocalDateTime deserialize(JsonElement json, Type typeOfT, JsonDeserializationContext context) throws JsonParseException {
        return LocalDateTime.parse(json.getAsString(), DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;));
    }
}

```

and then in your class you need to annotate your field (I left out any validations so it&#39;s easier to follow/understand):

```java
...

@JsonAdapter(MyDateDeserializer.class)
private LocalDateTime createdAt;

...
```

I haven&#39;t used GSON in a very long time so there might be an easier way but this should work as well.

PS. I would also discourage you to use Lombok because once it gets entangled into a project is almost impossible to get rid of. Just let your IDE generate the getters, setters, constructors, equals methods, hash codes etc.

