When polymorphic classes are used in a REST API, Jackson can&#39;t determine which type of `CompleteRequest` subclasses should be instantiated for each list element.

In your particular case, the list elements are instantiated as  `CompleteRequest` objects, thus ignoring unused fields. Consequently, those objects cannot be cast to child classes, so the `ClassCastException` is thrown.

One simple way to handle this is to define a type hint, as follows:
```java
@Getter
@AllArgsConstructor
@JsonTypeInfo(use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME, property = &quot;type&quot;)
@JsonSubTypes({
    @JsonSubTypes.Type(value=DataRequest.class, name = &quot;DataRequest&quot;),
    @JsonSubTypes.Type(value=TagRequest.class, name = &quot;TagRequest&quot;)
})
@NoArgsConstructor
public class CompleteRequest {...}
```
The `type` property should be added to the request body, which would Jackson use to determine which subclass to instantiate.
```
[
    {
        &quot;type&quot;: &quot;TagRequest&quot;,
        &quot;name&quot;: &quot;John&quot;,
        &quot;user_name&quot;: &quot;johnny&quot;,
        &quot;email&quot;: &quot;johny@gmail.com&quot;,
        &quot;phone&quot;: &quot;0000&quot;,
        &quot;id&quot;: &quot;435445&quot;,
        &quot;tag&quot;: &quot;zxcvb&quot;
    },
    {
        &quot;type&quot;: &quot;DataRequest&quot;,
        &quot;name&quot;: &quot;John&quot;,
        &quot;user_name&quot;: &quot;johnny&quot;,
        &quot;email&quot;: &quot;johny@gmail.com&quot;,
        &quot;phone&quot;: &quot;0000&quot;,
        &quot;business&quot;: &quot;abcd&quot;,
        &quot;data&quot;: &quot;qwert&quot;
    }
]
```

To make it work add a default constructor to the subclasses by marking them with `@NoArgsConstructor`.


----

If you have no way to change the incoming payload or must not do so, the `DEDUCTION` type for the `@JsonTypeInfo` annotation, introduced in the `2.12` version of Jackson, can be used. But, as Xobotun mentioned in [his answer][2]:

&gt; I&#39;d still recommend to use `use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME`, as the new way [may throw an exception](https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind/blob/fc56ab2e07980b9e2a4316272b99fef57f2a64bb/src/main/java/com/fasterxml/jackson/databind/jsontype/impl/AsDeductionTypeDeserializer.java#L84) in complex cases when it has no way to determine which subtype to use.

Since this case is pretty simple you don&#39;t have to worry.

```java
@Getter
@AllArgsConstructor
@JsonTypeInfo(use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.DEDUCTION)
@JsonSubTypes({
    @JsonSubTypes.Type(value=DataRequest.class),
    @JsonSubTypes.Type(value=TagRequest.class)
})
@NoArgsConstructor
public class CompleteRequest {...}
```

For reference: [Applying polymorphism to a REST API using Spring Boot][1]

  [1]: https://totheroot.io/article/applying-polymorphism-to-a-rest-api-using-spring-boot
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/65685243/10231374

If you use &#39;CompleteRequest&#39; as the request body, you will lose all data that is unknown to the &#39;CompleteRequest&#39; class. Consequently, your JSONs will be serialized to the &#39;CompleteRequest&#39; object in the request, which doesn&#39;t contain any fields other than the four defined ones. See:
[![enter image description here][1]][1]

So, you need to specify a request object that contains all the fields you can send in JSONs, such as:

    @Getter
    @AllArgsConstructor
    public class CompleteRequest {
        @JsonProperty(&quot;name&quot;)
        private String name = null;
    
        @JsonProperty(&quot;user_name&quot;)
        private String userName = null;
    
        @JsonProperty(&quot;email&quot;)
        private String email = null;
    
        @JsonProperty(&quot;phone&quot;)
        private String phone = null;
    
        @JsonProperty(&quot;id&quot;)
        private String id = null;
    
        @JsonProperty(&quot;tag&quot;)
        private String tag = null;
    
        @JsonProperty(&quot;business&quot;)
        private String business = null;
    
        @JsonProperty(&quot;data&quot;)
        private String data = null;


When you receive a request, you can obtain the required fields (regarding class naming, your &#39;CompleteRequest&#39; is more like a &#39;PartialRequest.&#39;).

In this case, the &#39;DataController&#39; will look like this:

    @RestController
    @Slf4j
    public class DataController {
        @PostMapping(&quot;/data&quot;)
        DataResponse createData(@RequestBody List&lt;CompleteRequest&gt; completeRequests) {
            log.info(&quot;completeRequests = {}&quot;, completeRequests);
            DataResponse response = new DataResponse();
            response.setName(completeRequests.get(0).getName());
            response.setUserName(completeRequests.get(0).getUserName());
            response.setEmail(completeRequests.get(0).getEmail());
            response.setPhone(completeRequests.get(0).getPhone());
    //        response.setId(((TagRequest) completeRequests.get(0)).getId());
    //        response.setTag(((TagRequest) completeRequests.get(0)).getTag());
    //        response.setBusiness(((DataRequest) completeRequests.get(1)).getBusiness());
    //        response.setData(((DataRequest) completeRequests.get(1)).getData());
            response.setId(completeRequests.get(0).getId());
            response.setTag(completeRequests.get(0).getTag());
            response.setBusiness(completeRequests.get(1).getBusiness());
            response.setData(completeRequests.get(1).getData());
            return response;
        }
    }

Also, process null values in the request (i.e., don&#39;t set null values). Another way is to just use a `List&lt;Object&gt;` in the request. It will be cast to a LinkedHashMap, and you can process it as a map. Alternatively, use a `List&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt;` as the request:

    @PostMapping(&quot;/data&quot;)
        DataResponse createData(@RequestBody List&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt; completeRequests) {
            log.info(&quot;completeRequests = {}&quot;, completeRequests);
            DataResponse response = new DataResponse();
            response.setName(completeRequests.get(0).get(&quot;name&quot;));
            response.setUserName(completeRequests.get(0).get(&quot;user_name&quot;));
            response.setEmail(completeRequests.get(0).get(&quot;email&quot;));
            response.setPhone(completeRequests.get(0).get(&quot;phone&quot;));
            response.setId(completeRequests.get(0).get(&quot;id&quot;));
            response.setTag(completeRequests.get(0).get(&quot;tag&quot;));
            response.setBusiness(completeRequests.get(1).get(&quot;business&quot;));
            response.setData(completeRequests.get(1).get(&quot;data&quot;));
            return response;
        }




  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/hicNT.png

